Patients will be given access to 'transformative' HIV treatment from September, following the Supreme Court's decision on funding the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10 000 patients over a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the trial period after an appeal court upheld a Supreme Court decision last year stating that the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite statements that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England's Chief Executive Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients, with additional clinics to join in October and full implementation across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
PrEP before sex means that there is enough of a specific drug in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested included gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who were not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign consent to participate in the trial, including men, women, transsexuals and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by the appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also register with their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in the trial.
The programme will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England has signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international public contract.
The pilot period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and large-scale implementation.
Simon Stevens added: This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of efforts to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust, said, "We are witnessing a watershed moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is given correctly and to patients at risk, it offers the potential to turn the English HIV epidemic around.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require the need to persuade a partner, leading to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this declaration.'
Ian Green, the executive director of the Terrence Higgins Trust said, "The number one priority must be to rapidly roll out testing across the country; we must make it available to every patient.
We now have an experimental PrEP drug and are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV".
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
The evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing across the country as soon as possible to protect those exposed to HIV and together to stop the spread of HIV in society.'
