A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the Fridman Gallery in New York, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black, and brown - hanging from the ceiling on wires, each of them as if out of the previous one's eye.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral extracts and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally leaking classified cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before he left office.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to represent what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg has created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the submissiveness of DNA - as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken out about her self-identification as a woman since she was a young girl, and was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were withheld by prison staff, with only one black-and-white photograph leaked to the public in inferior quality, showing Manning, visibly distressed, sitting in the driver's seat in a platinum-blonde wig, to which she is now attached.
In 2015, there was still a positive response to the Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions from 2012.
In this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible similarities between these people.
And just about this time, she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait to the article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
But no visitors or photographs were allowed, so they contacted Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
In fact, President Obama asked for Manning's release a few days after the comic book was published, which was a welcome change after several excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
It's interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war against people who seek to leak government information and transgender soldiers, while he's trying to find new ways to incite anger with his tweets in areas he should be supporting.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that 'everything happens for a reason'.
Under a statement by the artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls out with her huge signature (the letter i in her last name is printed with a heart) for an end to the self-serving factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a hundredth of the letters C, G and A written in pencil.
By arranging the 200 letters (or nucleotides, in the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope people will take away from this that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way", said Dewey-Hagborg.
DNA tells many different stories, here's 30 of them.
The last exhibit, in a separate room, is a single page from the graphic novel mentioned above.
It shows Manning emerging in a King Kong fashion from the United States Disciplinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in his hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win", it says.
Never let yourself be silenced.
"It's a direct transcript of one of the letters", said the Philadelphia artist.
When I think about it, my skin just jumps.
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition in person -- as predicted in the comic book -- but when she does, she will be welcomed in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic images, lined up like a protest crowd.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly six foot tall statue of Manning, which is a pencil-shaped record of her genetic haplogroups.
"They've been on the walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to have a sense of the crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
I wanted to create the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her.
