Startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but she couldn't find the right survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And even though she promised anonymity for the survey, some employees expressed distrust of the entire process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity", said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for help from outside.
New HR startups are constantly appearing on the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee obligations, startups enable companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer total employee anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases even allow whistleblowers to bypass superiors and contact direct managers.
"There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glitter, she gained more insight into what her employees were thinking and feeling over the past three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting of specific teams, Glint offers a company heat map and a snapshot of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as a snapshot of the managers with the lowest ratings - allowing users to work on correction.
Companies are starting to realize that they need to look out for the workplace culture - in case they become another Uber - which is mired in scandals after a former employee posted a blog post describing the company environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the website Let's Talk Payments, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Nearly 600 of Convercent's clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He recently took Uber under his wing.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send out customizable flash surveys, collect confidential information in real time and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The court of public opinion has its regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of startup Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreating its employees or unethical behaviour - and if regulators do not intervene - it may face costly consequences from customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain that employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employee awareness of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate management.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to find a phone number or an e-mail address for the company management, file a formal complaint, and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, who said there had been no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now, with Convercent, the company ensures that problems that never before reached managers sitting in their offices, miles away from the actual resolution of complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment - are detected and resolved quickly.
"It's moving towards a holistic, holistic view of the employee experience", said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
We also protect shareholders from employee litigation.
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron's fall over employee ethics abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until social media shed light on the whole thing that companies started to realize that in the online world they can't just hide their skeletons in the closet.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith", Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service for which the companies pay regular fees.
It's a business model and an opportunity that's been embraced by the bold venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
Convercent raised a total of $10 million in its February campaign from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and ultimately took out $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November, and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of the companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing number of studies clearly confirm that employees today expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high wages and exciting projects aren't the main advantage.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated and that they are giving their time to a company that is striving for a positive mission.
"If people are happy at their jobs, feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they are striving for the success of the company", said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when companies are successful, and companies prosper when their employees are happy.
And when an analytics tool comes to market that ensures employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's no wonder there are a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless society takes the necessary action.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can happen.
And if change is not made quickly - at worst - it can cause frustration and disinterest among employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations", said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has seen many companies rely too heavily on data alone.
Because once you don't get things done, the employees start asking themselves, "Did they hear me?
They're interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, which now conducts a regular monthly employee survey, can solve the problem within a day with Glinth, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by the slow decision-making and the quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important insight into its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term in an industry known for frequent layoffs.
"If you don't work to create a transparent work environment, employees won't trust you", added Vitrano.
And once you start losing employees, you're going to lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt.
