Facebook plans to do more fact-checking to reduce the number of fake news
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles for third-party review and display findings under original posts in an effort to combat so-called fake news, the largest social network said Thursday.
The company states in a statement on its website that it will start using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes, which it will send to third parties for verification and potentially display the results of the survey under the original contributions.
Facebook has been called one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports influenced the U.S. presidential election last year.
Political debate is raging in Europe, French voters are being inundated with fake news about the May presidential election, and Germany is planning to fine the social media network if it does not remove angry posts quickly ahead of the September election.
In a separate statement issued in Germany on Thursday, Facebook said it was going to test a new fake news feature in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
"Beyond seeing news verified by third parties, people are asking for more content to be better informed and to make informed decisions about what to share", Sara Su, Facebook's product news manager, wrote on her blog.
She added that Facebook is continuing to test the "Related Articles" feature and is also working on further changes to reduce the number of fake news.
Creating a graphic novel: A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently featured in a music video by the band Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher also found refuge there during the 1970s and 1980s.
But from his cozy little spot on the Bewl River in Kent, England, Scotney witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history that inspired the furry Jamie Rhodes of Yorkshire - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the handwriting of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me", Rhodes says with a serious face.
When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.
A Castle in England, a graphic novel, documents the lives of the families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period, each story illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives, however: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of British Library inspired documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the '70s who worked for the Jacobites", he said.
It's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because back then you had to light a candle to read them.
Smelling the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I've been back in time.
I love the archives!
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to spend almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian New Castle, going through the archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the hyenas' heads on the walls and bottles that had been thrown in the trenches for centuries.
He walked the grounds and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to the tenants, gardeners and occasionally the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
He drank whiskey and wrote at night.
Scotney's confidential history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain access to the documents until 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, the staff had only begun to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described in words like aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands around with the words, "Take it to the attic".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of property: "You may think a land dispute is boring", Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a barn.
Stop it people!
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a jumping-off point and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
"I found a record of a rebellion at the castle in 1380, which was called in a book the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex", said Rhodes.
The English uprising actually started in this area, and I thought a rebellion was a good place to start.
Maybe they're connected after all.
Other stories are firmly linked to the castle's history - such as The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was not discovered until years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was fascinated by the male generation - men were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrells have dealt with this by marrying rich or old brides - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to rub heads with heirs.
With his stay at the castle over, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he was taking inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was absorbed by nature.
But it's a strange place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left", he said.
I was like, "Now I'm going to get back to the real world".
