Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: A diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects as many as 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are usually told to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan, found in a protein, helps build immune cells that promote intestinal resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure that harmful microbes are broken down from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In the study, the researchers detected the presence of immune cells that promote tolerance in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
These bacteria require the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between a species of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a common part of the gut microbiome, and the development of cells that promote tolerance in the body.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.
He also suggested that if the same is found to be true in humans, then combining L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
As a postgraduate researcher, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, studied a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance in the body, and she found that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice had no cells.
She concluded that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally inhabit the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice's intestines were tested using DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the other group of mice lacked.
So mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome -- so they didn't develop this type of immune cells -- were given L. reuteri -- and they developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without the bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it was shown to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-octanoic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent, and when they halved the dose of tryptophan, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in the tryptophan-related genes have been detected in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Everyone should probably strive to develop these cells, because they control inflammation of the inner surface of the intestine.
Potentially high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population.
