The White House props cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn for the American manufacturing celebration last month came in at $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME magazine.
The green white Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One with the President on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials were touring the product show from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was parked next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a fork lift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn in a "emergency" event, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of this momentous event", the commander of HMX-1 wrote in an e-mail to his superior, the deputy commander of the Navy for aviation the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17th at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the parade, scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m., and would remain in place until the entire site was cleared, which was scheduled between 6:00 and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail also said that if there was a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to the working hours regulations.
The original crew stayed that evening, along with the helicopter and a security team.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it was unclear whether a second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prohibits government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible infringements of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a Hatch Act violation and were assured that everything was in order", the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you're being blocked", the deputy commander wrote back.
This "Made in America" parade was designated by the White House as an official event and therefore would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
In his participation at the event, the president pushed for health care reform, which passed the Senate and spoke of efforts to keep government regulations in check.
The use of air transport such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation purposes is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane flew in the background at his first-ever campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is pleased with the 'Made in America' show, which showcased products from all 50 states that are made by Americans from American materials", said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often practice landing in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, and practice possible arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with maximum precision.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew's ongoing training, a government official said.
The helicopter unit flew for another 11 hours on the same day as part of "non-presidential support missions".
The White House said no additional props were paid out of taxpayer money.
Sikorsky's spokesman stated that the company was not involved in any way in the negotiations to display the helicopter on South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights and the exact costs associated with the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, DoD expense reimbursement for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records show time 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopters are well below that amount.
"It is very misleading to list taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for the reimbursement of expenditure", Walters said of the whole matter.
These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs which are included in the annual costs.
The Commission notes that the State aid granted to the airport in question is not compatible with the internal market.
White House press secretary Sean Spicer at the time advocated the use of helicopters for the purpose of the parade.
"The idea of the show, which is taking place this week, is to showcase products made in the U.S"., said Spicer.
I am aware that the Sikorsky Corporation and the State of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state and that they are providing employment to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we're proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens have been involved in making.
This is a fact worthy of remembrance.
It's unclear whether Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his tour of the South Lawn, but it's safe to say that he was behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky's representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well", said the President, "I own three of them".
